AB  - It is foreseen that traditional ways of road tolling will be substituted by solutions based on positioning by means of GNSS in a few years. These new solutions are very promising because of their low cost for large infrastructures as well as their flexibility. It is clear that road tolling simulation tools constitute a powerful element for the evaluation of these emerging systems. The applicability of these simulation tools is wide, from the design and preliminary evaluation of a tolling system before being established, to the evaluation of the improvement in the tolling performances with the inclusion of Galileo. Road tolling based on GNSS implies that the position and trajectory of a vehicle is estimated by means of a GNSS system in order to decide if the vehicle must be charged and to compute the charging value. A road tolling simulation tool should be capable of computing an estimation of the charging performances based on parameters related to the quality of the GNSS navigation solution and its environment, like User Equivalent Range Error (UERE) values, Dilution of Precision (DOP) matrices, geometry and multipath in urban canyons. The assessment of the tolling system performance to be evaluated by the simulator will be represented by concepts such as the charging availability and the overcharging. In addition, the road tolling simulator would have to provide statistical analysis over the time of these figures of merit. In this way, the different quality of the navigation solution for different epochs as the GNSS constellations evolve will be considered. The possibility of modification of all the parameters involved in the road tolling system definition is a desired characteristic for developing trade-off simulations between several tolling systems. Recently, the GMV Polaris tool has been upgraded with road tolling evaluation and simulation capabilities, in line with the characteristics mentioned in the paragraph above. Polaris computes now tolling performances based on a UERE model provided as input and DOP matrices computed for each time epoch of the simulation. The tool will consider different GNSS constellations (GPS/Galileo), augmentations (SBAS, differential GPS, pseudollites, UMTS) and hybridations (odometers, gyroscopes, accelerometers⋯). Regarding the statistical analysis over the time, it allows the inclusion of satellite failure models that are very useful to obtain more realistic results. The simulation performance results are showed in graphical and textual modes for a fast evaluation of the quality of the road tolling system. With its new road tolling simulation capabilities, Polaris becomes a key tool for the design and validation of the incoming GNSS based tolling systems for technicians and decision makers.
