AB  - Requirements to be met by satellite data provision for natural disaster management are specially demanding in terms of timeliness from activation to image sensing and delivery. This paper reflects the operational approach set up by DEIMOS-1 for rush data provision in emergency exercises using two examples. The February 2012 flood event in Australia impacted over 100,000 km2. DEIMOS-1, in cooperation with Astrium Geo-Information Services - Australia, triggered an emergency campaign following a three-step methodology: image rush tasking according to local knowledge of flood location from emergency service staff, rush delivery of a 300m/pixel quicklook of the acquired images a few hours after sensing (for evaluation of cloudiness and first assessment of flooded areas), rush delivery of full-resolution orthorectified images a few hours after sensing for in-depth analysis of real flood conditions. This procedure was carried out by the DEIMOS-1 24/7 team and up to 26 images were delivered from early February to mid March 2012. DEIMOS-1 imagery was processed by the National Earth Observation group within Geoscience Australia to map the flood extents and evaluate affected roads, houses and infrastructure (bridges, culverts, and small dams). A similar campaign has been run by Elecnor Deimos Imaging to observe with DEIMOS-1 the forest fires in Spain between June and September 2012. The service included the systematic acquisition of all possible images over the country, the identification of affected areas and the rapid generation of thematic maps and quantitative analyses. All value added products were made available just one working day after the image sensing. This service provided pre- And post-event images of two large fires to the European Space Agency in the frame of a GMES emergency activation (with delivery of archive images in less than one hour), and burned areas maps to the Spanish Ministry of Agriculture, Food and Environment. Copyright © (2013) by the Ameri