AB  - Will Galileo make a significant difference to maritime navigation in challenging operational environments? The expected and intuitive answer to the question is 'yes'. However, in order to substantiate this claim it is necessary to bridge the gap between performance evaluation of existing GNSS systems and identification of their weaknesses, and the existence of concrete scientific evidence that supports the use of Galileo in order to overcome these weaknesses. In the absence of the real Galileo system, simulation is the only recourse. Thales Research & Technology (UK) Ltd., TRT, have developed and utilised the Thales Integrated Navigation Test-bed, TINT, to confirm and quantify any potential benefits arising from the introduction of the Galileo satellite positioning system. The TINT facilitates the simulation of maritime mission scenarios, providing a good characterisation of GNSS navigation signals for both GPS and Galileo and the means by which they are processed to produce a navigation solution. Furthermore, this characterisation accounts for all operational and environmental factors that significantly affect the performance of a GNSS system. The mission scenarios are intended to support the investigation of the potential of Galileo to improve upon current GNSS-based maritime navigation system performance and as such, are aligned with the three of the MARUSE† maritime demonstrations: • A ship entering Trondheim harbour in Norway and docking. • A ship navigating within Oban sound in Scotland in a manner representative of an Aid to Navigation, AtoN, management scenario. • Inland waterway navigation of barge entering and exiting the Djerdap lock complex on the River Danube in Serbia. Significantly, the Oban mission scenario also addresses the use of a local element (LE) in the form of Galileo pseudolites to augment the positioning performance in a challenging operational environment. The paper introduces the TINT simulation facility and provides an overview of the functionality it offers. In particular, there is a strong emphasis on the capability to simulate realistic multipath characteristics, derived from complex 3-D models, a key requirement in order to support the analysis of navigation performance in the challenging environments. The paper continues by describing in more detail these challenging environments and the three mission scenarios. For each scenario, test cases were carefully chosen in order to cover a broad spectrum of operational conditions and produce a rich set of navigation system performance results. The analysis of these results is then targeted to provide performance characteristics in terms of accuracy, integrity, continuity and availability that will help quantify to what extent the introduction of Galileo can be expected to improve GNSS based maritime navigation system performance. Results and analysis are presented for both absolute and differential solutions for combined GPS and Galileo GNSS navigation performance versus single GNSS navigation performance; assessed under malign conditions with severe satellite signal multipath and obscuration and compared to a benign operational environment. The ability of pseudolites to improve positioning performance is also determined. Finally, the paper summarises the findings, which although in general agree with the intuitive and expected answer predicted in the introduction, it identifies specific conditions where this is not always the case and examines the reason for this.
