AB  - In the large area, there is a tendency towards higher water demands than in the past, so significant water storage, such as reservoirs and canals, has been added in the watershed area. On the one hand floods often occur during the rainy season, because there are rain storms and excessive water in the reservoirs. On the other hand, during the dry season there is insufficient water, because water in the reservoirs is released without accurate planning during the rainy season. Thus, improving water resources management is becoming more and more necessary. The purpose of this session is to calculate water budget for the accurate planning of water management. Then, there are three main parts of this research: actual evapotranspiration; rainfall; and water budget. First, actual evapotranspiration was calculated by SEBAL and the FAO Penman-Montieth equation. The time period for actual evapotranspiration calculations from SEBAL and from the FAO Penman-Monteith computations is one year. In the SEBAL method, MODIS images were used for daily actual evapotranspiration estimation, while weather data from weather stations was used to produce daily actual evapotranspiration using the FAO Penman-Monteith equation. Thereafter, actual evapotranspiration values calculated from the FAO Penman-Monteith method were compared with actual evapotranspiration values calculated from SEBAL to determine the suitable actual evapotranspiration for the calculation of water budgets. Second, rainfall was obtained from TRMM images and rain gauge stations. The time period for rainfall data from TRMM images and from rain gauge stations is one year. Thereafter, monthly rainfalls from TRMM image were compared with monthly rainfall from rain gauge station to determine the suitable monthly rainfall for the calculation of water budgets. Finally, monthly water budgets were calculated. The main inflow for basin is rainfall, while the main outflow for each basin is actual evapotranspiration. Then, monthly actual evapotranspiration and monthly rainfall were utilized for the monthly water budget calculations. Regarding, the contribution of this session, the combination of evapotranspiration and rainfall from satellite imagery to compute water budget in large scale is new. Accordingly, after the results that can be applied to river basins and analyzing water management, the methodology can also be applied in other countries around the world. © 2010 by World Scientific Publishing Co. Pte. Ltd. All rights reserved.
