AB  - This paper describes a study (2013-16 period) on some technological and economic data extracted from the Panel of firms registered in ASI's (Italian Space Agency) DV web db and portal, with the aim of assessing the sector's capacity to transfer space technology into business, in both the so called â€œspace relatedâ€ and â€œspace enabledâ€ areas. The Panel hereabove is estimated to cover 90% of the sector and applies methodologies, metrics and definitions - see especially those describing the above areas, as separate fields from the core space upstream and downstream domain - shared with the main international boards on space statistics (OECD, IAF). ESA even took inspiration from these methodologies and definitions within a Pilot test instrument, now on its website (Space Economy section - Global Space Economy Forum), to collect and compare space economic data from Member Countries. This work concentrates on the technological part of the study, which otherwise provided economic insights of a growing activity estimated 5-10% compared to the space production value, considering in the count also business transferred for its management to dedicated subsidiaries. The mainstay definition applied to these activities is in their being connected to space but not crucially, at a level, so to say, where â€œthey could also exist withoutâ€ space. In this, they differentiate from the so called general space â€œdownstreamâ€, whereas the rule relays for us on the opposite statement or â€¦ â€œthey could not exist withoutâ€. The definition above firstly applies to a closer and bordering layer (to the downright space activity area) of activities which we define as â€œspace relatedâ€, where space technologies are ongoing but their integration is not absolutely necessary, as happens with communication and localization services in urban areas. It is the case for instance of Sat tv and Car sharing (that could also rely on different terrestrial technologies), or smartphones or insurance services assisted by satellite positioning. Connected to the latter, and much more interesting for our purposes, layer of activities, that we define â€œspace enabledâ€, where space technologies are only the â€œtriggerâ€ of their terrestrial development, which ensues independently. A list of cases of this "layer" is offered, covering supermaterials and industrial subsystems (fashion brand accessories, car consoles, optical semiconductors, refrigerators), aeronautics hardware (radars, emergency floaters devices, parachutes, ground service devices), medical scanning devices and applications, industrial test and R&D equipment, telemetric systems for sport cars. It appears hence that space has a wide innovative industrial potential due to its top quality and performance standards, or, in other terms, that the extreme space challenge, enhances competitivity for ensueing terrestrial uses. It is finally appearing that the firms having these capacities are also better performing by space standards, in production and employment terms, and therefore provide leverage for public strategies. Copyright © 2018 by the International Astronautical Federation (IAF). All rights reserved.
