AB  - There is nothing novel in the idea of hosting secondary payloads on communications satellites. Using the unused spacecraft resources typically held as margin for a secondary payload has potentially great benefits for all parties involved. Unfortunately the idea of hosted payloads has been poorly executed. The number of communications satellites that have secondary payloads compared to the number that could have had secondary payloads is miniscule. Part of the problem is the very narrow focus on the technical challenges of secondary payload hosting, with no view to the economic and organizational challenges. One great challenge of successful secondary payload hosting is to bridge the organizational differences between the host spacecraft providers-almost always privately held commercial entities-and the payload providers-typically defense or science related offices of the government. The organizational differences appear in all program phases, from hardware procurement to development to execution. Between these organizations there exists a major difference in the goals and views of the space assets entirely. Revenue generation is the ultimate reason for bringing a commercial payload to space while the unique vantage point for observation is the reason that draws science and military interests. Free market economics with the aim of maximizing profit margins, and minimizing non recurring costs has enabled commercial space to routinely execute commercial missions from start of contract to launch in two years or less at prices a fraction of those of government run missions. Indeed, when government sponsored missions operate to similar time lines it is usually a cause for celebrations and press releases. Unfortunately the government entities interested in having their secondary payloads hosted often find alien and challenging the very streamlined approach and efficiencies which make commercial space so attractive. A further complexity of the issue is that different entities within the government sponsored science and defense agencies have their own nuanced views as well as payloads that are intended to fulfill different functions such as operations, basic science, defense, or technology demonstration. Science and defense organizations do not operate the same way. Integrating payloads from such different backgrounds within a single mission will inevitably lead to both procedural and technical implications for the interfaces. This paper identifies the difficulties arising from such differences and discusses the efforts to develop a standardized technical interface and integration process to bring together a combined mission consisting of a privately owned and operated spacecraft containing the primary communications and secondary hosted payloads. Understanding and flexibility both are needed to achieve a symbiotic relationship that allows for cost saving of all parties while not slowing down the pace or making inefficient the commercial aspect of the mission while still accommodating the different mission requirements and procedural differences of the host payload provider. Copyright © 2008 by Phillip Kalmanson of Orbital Sciences Corporation.
