AB  - Indian Earth Observation (EO) programme since its inception has been application driven. It has evolved from experimental satellites, operational satellites to present generation of theme specific satellites. Theme specific EO satellites have been categorized in three categories: Land, Cartography and Ocean and Atmosphere theme observation satellites. Indian EO capabilities has increased manifold. Improvements are not only in spatial, spectral, temporal and radiometric resolution but also in their coverage and value added products. In the coming 10 years, India has planned more than 20 satellites carrying imaging and non-imaging sensors with varieties of capabilities and complexities. It will have microwave, hyperspectral, stereo viewing, high resolution imaging from geo-synchronous platform etc., which will fulfill the present and future gap areas in EO applications. A variety of data products will be obtained from multiple missions for multiple themes with emphasis on actionable products and services. In order to realize these missions and derive maximum benefits, a number of areas related to ground segment need to be addressed like multi-mission acquisition and processing, effective delivery mechanisms, real time web-based services and mission oriented outreach activities. A comprehensive standardization effort is called for to acquire, manage, process and disseminate these datasets to meet the various application requirements and user needs, like global change applications, mapping and cartographic applications, natural resources and environmental management applications and disaster management. For example, in generating the spatial information, satellite images and maps form the foundation and basis for most planning and implementation of various natural resources management/environmental applications. Hence, standardization is a must in systematic spatial dataset creation at various stages in the total process of spatial information generation upto its final delivery that enables uniformity and flexibility in mapping and GIS database organization. These standards enable technologies - imaging and GIS applications - thematic mapping, services and outputs etc. to work together, increase interoperability, brings systematization and automation of mapping and GIS so that it will generate the actionable products and services. Again, for dissemination of spatial data and application services, effective delivery mechanism need to be worked out which will be on real time basis, easily accessible and faster to achieve the critical needs of weather forecasting, disaster monitoring etc. The present paper brings out about glimpse of various applications and beneficiaries, various elements of standardization in the area of EO data, maps, applications, database organization and delivery mechanism in order to cater the various users applications where importance of having satellite data and timeliness is very important. Copyright IAF/IAA. All rights reserved.
